## The Core Concept

A **process** is an independent program with its own memory space. A **thread** is a lightweight unit of execution *within* a process — threads share memory with each other.

---

## CPU-Bound vs I/O-Bound Tasks

| | CPU-Bound | I/O-Bound |
|---|---|---|
| **Bottleneck** | Processor speed | Waiting (disk, network, DB) |
| **Example** | Matrix math, compression, ML training | Web requests, file reads, DB queries |
| **CPU usage** | Always high | Low — CPU sits idle while waiting |

---

## What Happens at the OS Level

### Threads — Shared Memory, One GIL (in Python)

```
Process A
├── Thread 1 ──► OS Scheduler ──► CPU Core 1
├── Thread 2 ──► OS Scheduler ──► CPU Core 1  ← same core! (Python GIL)
└── Thread 3 ──► OS Scheduler ──► CPU Core 1
     └── Shared heap memory (all threads see the same data)
```

- The OS schedules threads via **context switching** — rapidly pausing one thread and resuming another
- In Python, the **GIL (Global Interpreter Lock)** prevents true parallel execution of Python bytecode → only one thread runs at a time
- BUT: the GIL is **released during I/O waits**, so threads still shine for I/O-bound work

### Processes — Isolated Memory, True Parallelism

```
Process A ──► CPU Core 1   (own memory space)
Process B ──► CPU Core 2   (own memory space)
Process C ──► CPU Core 3   (own memory space)
     └── No shared memory — must use IPC (pipes, queues, shared memory)
```

- Each process gets its **own GIL** → true parallel CPU execution
- OS treats each as independent — separate PID, memory, file descriptors
- Heavier to spawn (fork/exec), higher memory cost

